<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Raiding Guidelines</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Overall Rules</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<br>
THE most important rule: Listen, pay attention, and do what you're told. <br>
<br>
<br>
Listen to the Raid leader and your group leader. Follow their directions. If you think there's a better way, tell your group leader and he/she can pass that on.<br>
<br>
Don't question the raid leader during the raid. If you disagree with something he or she says, then talk to him/her AFTER the raid.<br>
<br>
Don't send tells to the raid leader unless you absolutely have to. Talk to your group leader instead. The raid leader is probably in tell hell for the duration of the raid.<br>
<br>
Stay for the duration of the Raid. If you suddenly have to go for a real life emergency, make sure that the raid leader and group leader know of it. <br>
<br>
2-boxing is generally discouraged.<br>
<br>
Show up early. If you're late, there's no guarantee that you can join the raid.<br>
<br>
Be polite. Do NOT criticize, demean or otherwise be mean to anyone in any raid channel.<br>
<br>
The raid leader reserves the right to boot any character from the raid for disorderly conduct. Booted characters may or may not be offered a translocate to bind or the nexus.<br>
<br>
Know your job. Ask your group leader if you're unsure of what you're supposed to do. Do not assume that you know your job .. check!<br>
<br>
Do some research on the zone BEFORE the raid. At least have some idea of the general layout and objectives. The more you know, the better a raider you'll be.<br>
<br>
Be prepared to die. Deaths are something good raid leaders try to avoid, but they happen. Raids with no deaths are VERY rare.<br>
<br>
Be PATIENT. The hardest part about a raid is waiting, but you've got to do it so you give the buffers and leaders enough time to organize. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Chat Channels</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Raid channel: either a chat channel or the /raidchat channel if we're using the PoP raid system. This channel should be used for incoming, assist and MA/SA heal announcements as well as for any raid wide announcements (moving, information on the mobs, adds, etc). Please keep this channel as clear as possible.<br>
<br>
Group chat: The /gsay channel. This channel is for group conversations, heal announcements, and general questions about the raid.<br>
<br>
Group Leader channel (optional): This is a channel for the group leaders and raid leaders to communicate without tells.<br>
<br>
Healer channel (optional): A channel for the Healer coordinator to communicate with the raid healers. LOM, OOM announcements should go to this channel as well as to the group chat.<br>
<br>
Other channels may be added as the raid leader sees fit.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Gathering &amp; Grouping</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The raid channel will be announced before hand and communicated as much as possible through guild chats and standard chat channels prior to the raid.<br>
<br>
Please arrive at the gathering site 20 - 30 mins before the raid time for grouping. Please check in on the raid channel when you are on your way if you are less than 20 mins before the raid.<br>
<br>
Put LFG on and Role/Anon off when you are at the gathering spot. <br>
<br>
If you are going away from your computer for any reason , please put AFK on with a message for when you'll be back. E.g. /afk back in 2 mins<br>
<br>
Pay attention to the raid channel for group assignments. <br>
<br>
The MA and SA will be announced before we move in. Please set up your hotbuttons before we leave the gathering site.<br>
<br>
Please be patient. We try to pre-plan our groups as much as possible, but there are always last minute changes.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Looting</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
All loot will be awarded on a need before greed (NBG) basis. If it's not an upgrade for you, please do not roll unless it's announced that it's an open roll.<br>
<br>
Main looters will be assigned in each group. No one else should be looting. Anyone found looting without permission may not be allowed to roll on anything.<br>
<br>
Items may be rolled on during med breaks or lulls in the fighting at the raid leader's discretion.<br>
<br>
The raid leader will announce a safe spot to gather after the raid to split any remaining loot.<br>
<br>
Any plat for reagents will generally be reimbursed with coin/items before loot is split. Clerics/Chanters please keep track of how many reagents you use.<br>
<br>
Any reserved items will be announced prior to the raid.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>During the Raid</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Don't hit anything the MA or SA isn't already hitting. In cases where we do not have an enchanter, or the chanter is busy with the main mobs, adds should be rooted and someone will be designated to be the root-er. Roots with a damage component (rangers, druids) should be avoided if possible as this will break a chanter's mez. Let the chanters do their job.<br>
<br>
Stand up when you see the incoming message. Nothing pulls agro more than someone sitting down. Remain standing until the MT gets agro (usually at about 80% mob health)<br>
<br>
Do not attack until the assist is called. Casters should not nuke until the mob is at least at 70% life. Snare should not be cast until at least 50% or less of life. Slows/debuffs should be cast as soon as possible without pulling agro.<br>
<br>
The MA or the SA are the only people who should have agro. If you gain agro, do everything possible to lose it fast. Stop attacking and move to the MA. Go stand next to him or her. Don't start attacking until you lose agro.<br>
<br>
Don't root unless you're instructed to. Announce roots in the raid channel. <br>
<br>
If a mob has been rooted, and you are not the MA or SA, make sure that you are further from the mob than the MA/SA. Rooted mobs attack the person closest to them.<br>
<br>
If you're told to die, die. You might be sucking up the harm touch that allows everyone else to move forward. You'll be rezed as soon as possible. <br>
Watch for the Enrage message. I if a mob enrages and you're in front of it, turn off attack. No questions. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Additional Notes</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Mob Positioning</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
by Bombudil<br>
<br>
All melees have to learn something which can be very hard; mob positioning. Simply where the mob should be. With 20+ melee hacking and slashing at a creature, it will gain a great deal of momentum and be displaced during the course of the fight.<br>
This is bad for several reasons: <br>
* It can move the mob, and with it MA, out of range of the healing rotation (which is often stationary behind a wall, and cannot move to take mob dislocation into account).<br>
* It can move the mob, possibly a dragon with a large AE damage, into range of healers and casters (who will be hiding behind a wall).<br>
(An extreme example is the Guardian of NToV: Aaryonar. He is not a target that the GCP can hit for many months yet, but... He casts AE mana drain dot. If a caster is hit by Aary AE, he/she will lose 400 mana each tick (6 seconds). Only very experienced fighting teams will survive casters being hit by Aary AE <br>
* The mob can start spinning: If uneven pressure is applied to the mob, and this mostly starts when mob is moving, it will start to spin from the melee pressure. When a mob is spinning, the raid will lose valuable DPS from rogues who lose a clear backside, and MA will need to continously try to stay in front. Some higher level mobs also have a high riposte factor in that they riposte very often. Monks, rangers and rogues in general attack very very fast, and will normally not have much healing support (most healing being consentrated on MA). If the frontside of a mob should hit this bunch of melee, they can go down fast due to riposte damage.<br>
Of course, spinning a mob that is enraging is doubly bad, as it is riposting every attack made from the front. Nearly won raids can be lost due to spinning, enraging mobs.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Buffing:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
by Bombudil<br>
<br>
When buffing up for a raid, the following protocol should be applied:<br>
Group leaders are in charge of buffs for his or her group, and should request all buffs in /tells. I cannot stress this enough*.<br>
If the buff requested is a group buff, make sure everyone stays close.<br>
If the buff requested is single target, include the name of all targets (in the group) in the buff request.<br>
<br>
No one apart from group leaders are to ask for buffs.<br>
<br>
Exception: Haste. All melee are responsible for keeping up their own haste through requests to a haster (in tells, of course).<br>
<br>
Buffing will not happen 10 seconds before the mob is incoming. Buffers will give everyone ample time to get buffed up, but they have other jobs to take care off when the monks are shouting INC.<br>
<br>
*) The reasons being:<br>
-Most people will have tells filtered to a separate window, and buff requests won't be pushed out of the window by raid spam.<br>
-Buffers can use the /rt command to quickly target the source of the request.<br>
-Reducing information overload on raid channel. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Enrage</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
by Tethalia<br>
<br>
[Editors Note: Enrage is when the mob automatically reposts every attack made on it from the front.]<br>
<br>
ENRAGE is THE enemy. Forget the name of the mob or the zone that Capitalised word in red is the enemy ENRAGE. This is the second most frequent killer of rangers after pulling duties. It is common and you just have to get used to it. If you are not behind the mob when it enrages you will die and this is why. When you click off auto attack the next attack will happen anyway due to the time it takes your client to tell the server you stopped attacking. Murphy's law will strike and you will quad. A quad on vindi will get you 4 700-880 point reposts. Hands up all those with more than 3080 HP.... Ok not many... How many of you still have more than 1 bub of HP left?....<br>
